# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: memory-forensics-volatility
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] In computing, a **core dump**, **memory dump**, **crash dump**, **storage dump**, **system dump**, or **ABEND dump** consists of the recorded state of the working memory of a computer program at a specific time, generally when the program has crashed or otherwise terminated abnormally.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] In practice, other key pieces of program state are usually dumped at the same time, including the processor registers, which may include the program counter and stack pointer, memory management information, and other processor and operating system flags and information.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] A **snapshot dump** (or **snap dump**) is a memory dump requested by the computer operator or by the running program, after which the program is able to continue.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Core dumps are often used to assist in diagnosing and debugging errors in computer programs.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] On many operating systems, a fatal exception in a program automatically triggers a core dump.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] By extension, the phrase "to dump core" has come to mean in many cases, any fatal error, regardless of whether a record of the program memory exists.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The term "core dump", "memory dump", or just "dump" has also become jargon to indicate any output of a large amount of raw data for further examination or other purposes.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The name comes from magnetic-core memory, the principal form of random-access memory from the 1950s to the 1970s.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The name has remained long after magnetic-core technology became obsolete.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Earliest core dumps were paper printouts of the contents of memory, typically arranged in columns of octal or hexadecimal numbers (a "hex dump"), sometimes accompanied by their interpretations as machine language instructions, text strings, or decimal or floating-point numbers (*cf.* disassembler).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] As memory sizes increased and post-mortem analysis utilities were developed, dumps were written to magnetic media like tape or disk.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] In some operating systems an application or operator may request a snapshot of selected storage blocks, rather than all of the storage used by the application or operating system.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Core dumps can serve as useful debugging aids in several situations.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] On early standalone or batch-processing systems, core dumps allowed a user to debug a program without monopolizing the (very expensive) computing facility for debugging; a printout could also be more convenient than debugging using front panel switches and lights.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] On shared computers, whether time-sharing, batch processing, or server systems, core dumps allow off-line debugging of the operating system, so that the system can go back into operation immediately.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Core dumps allow a user to save a crash for later or off-site analysis, or comparison with other crashes.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] For embedded computers, it may be impractical to support debugging on the computer itself, so analysis of a dump may take place on a different computer.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Some operating systems such as early versions of Unix did not support attaching debuggers to running processes, so core dumps were necessary to run a debugger on a process's memory contents.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Core dumps can be used to capture data freed during dynamic memory allocation and may thus be used to retrieve information from a program that is no longer running.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] In the absence of an interactive debugger, the core dump may be used by an assiduous programmer to determine the error from direct examination.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Snap dumps are sometimes a convenient way for applications to record quick and dirty debugging output.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] A core dump generally represents the complete contents of the dumped regions of the address space of the dumped process.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Depending on the operating system, the dump may contain few or no data structures to aid interpretation of the memory regions.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] In these systems, successful interpretation requires that the program or user trying to interpret the dump understands the structure of the program's memory use.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] There are also special-purpose tools called dump analyzers to analyze dumps.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] One popular tool, available on many operating systems, is the GNU binutils' objdump.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] On modern Unix-like operating systems, administrators and programmers can read core dump files using the GNU Binutils Binary File Descriptor library (BFD), and the GNU Debugger (gdb) and objdump that use this library.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Analysts of crash dumps from Linux systems can use kdump or the Linux Kernel Crash Dump (LKCD).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Core dumps can save the context (state) of a process at a given state for returning to it later.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Systems can be made highly available by transferring core between processors, sometimes via core dump files themselves.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Core can also be dumped onto a remote host over a network (which is a security risk).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] OS/360 introduced the service aid IMDPRDMP to print stand-alone and SVC dumps.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] This program formats several system control blocks in addition to printing storage areas in hexadecimal and EBCDIC.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The OS/VS1 and OS/VS2 versions are called HMDPRDMP and AMDPRDMP.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Interactive Problem Control System (IPCS) is a full screen dump reader that IBM introduced for OS/VS2 (MVS), DOS/VSE and VM/370.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The MVS version performs functions similar to AMDPRDMP, and uses compatible control block descriptions for formatting.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] IBM eventually dropped AMDPRDMP in favor of IPCS.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] IPCS on MVS supports scripts in CLIST and REXX.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Users of IBM mainframes running z/OS can browse both SVC and transaction dumps using IPCS, which supports user written scripts in REXX and supports point-and-shoot browsing of dumps.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] In older and simpler operating systems, each process had a contiguous address-space, so a dump file was sometimes simply a file with the sequence of bytes, digits, characters or words.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] On other systems a dump file contained discrete records, each containing a storage address and the associated contents.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] On the earliest of these machines, the dump was often written by a stand-alone dump program rather than by the application or the operating system.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The IBSYS monitor for the IBM 7090 included a System Core-Storage Dump Program that supported post-mortem and snap dumps.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] On the IBM System/360, the standard operating systems wrote formatted ABEND and SNAP dumps, with the addresses, registers, storage contents, etc., all converted into printable forms.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] In modern operating systems, a process address space may contain gaps, and it may share pages with other processes or files, so more elaborate representations are used; they may also include other information about the state of the program at the time of the dump.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] In OS/360 and successors, a job may assign arbitrary data set names (dsnames) to the ddnames `SYSABEND` and `SYSUDUMP` for a formatted ABEND dump and to arbitrary ddnames for SNAP dumps, or define those ddnames as SYSOUT.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The Damage Assessment and Repair (DAR) facility added an automatic unformatted storage dump to the dataset `SYS1.DUMP` at the time of failure as well as a console dump requested by the operator.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] A job may assign an arbitrary dsname to the ddname `SYSMDUMP` for an unformatted ABEND dump, or define that ddname as SYSOUT.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The newer transaction dump is very similar to the older SVC dump.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The *Interactive Problem Control System* (IPCS), added to OS/VS2 by *Selectable Unit* (SU) 57 and part of every subsequent MVS release, can be used to interactively analyze storage dumps on DASD.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] IPCS understands the format and relationships of system control blocks, and can produce a formatted display for analysis.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The current versions of IPCS allow inspection of active address spaces without first taking a storage dump and of unformaated dumps on SPOOL.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Since Solaris 8, system utility `coreadm` allows the name and location of core files to be configured.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Dumps of user processes are traditionally created as `core`.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] System-wide dumps on modern Unix-like systems often appear as `vmcore` or `vmcore.incomplete`.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Systems such as Microsoft Windows, which use filename extensions, may use extension `.dmp`; for example, core dumps may be named `memory.dmp` or `\Minidump\Mini051509-01.dmp`.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Microsoft Windows supports two memory dump formats, described below.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] To analyze the Windows kernel-mode dumps Debugging Tools for Windows are used, a set that includes tools like WinDbg & DumpChk.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] User-mode memory dump, also known as *minidump*, is a memory dump of a single process.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] It contains selected data records: full or partial (filtered) process memory; list of the threads with their call stacks and state (such as registers or TEB); information about handles to the kernel objects; list of loaded and unloaded libraries.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Full list of options available in `MINIDUMP_TYPE` enum.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The NASA Voyager program was probably the first craft to routinely utilize the core dump feature in the Deep Space segment.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The core dump feature is a mandatory telemetry feature for the Deep Space segment as it has been proven to minimize system diagnostic costs.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] The Voyager craft uses routine core dumps to spot memory damage from cosmic ray events.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] Space Mission core dump systems are mostly based on existing toolkits for the target CPU or subsystem.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/core-dump] However, over the duration of a mission the core dump subsystem may be substantially modified or enhanced for the specific needs of the mission.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Various techniques have been developed to counter data remanence.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] These techniques are classified as clearing, purging/sanitizing, or destruction.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Specific methods include overwriting, degaussing, encryption, and media destruction.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Several standards exist for the secure removal of data and the elimination of data remanence.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Many operating systems, file managers, and other software provide a facility where a file is not immediately deleted when the user requests that action.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Instead, the file is moved to a holding area (i.e. the "trash"), making it easy for the user to undo a mistake.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Similarly, many software products automatically create backup copies of files that are being edited, to allow the user to restore the original version, or to recover from a possible crash (*autosave* feature).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Even when an explicit deleted file retention facility is not provided or when the user does not use it, operating systems do not actually remove the contents of a file when it is deleted unless they are aware that explicit erasure commands are required, like on a solid-state drive.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The data will remain there until the operating system reuses the space for new data.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] In some systems, enough filesystem metadata are also left behind to enable easy undeletion by commonly available utility software.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Even when undelete has become impossible, the data, until it has been overwritten, can be read by software that reads disk sectors directly.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Computer forensics often employs such software.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Likewise, reformatting, repartitioning, or reimaging a system is unlikely to write to every area of the disk, though all will cause the disk to appear empty or, in the case of reimaging, empty except for the files present in the image, to most software.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Finally, even when the storage media is overwritten, physical properties of the media may permit recovery of the previous contents.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] In most cases however, this recovery is not possible by just reading from the storage device in the usual way, but requires using laboratory techniques such as disassembling the device and directly accessing/reading from its components.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Clearing is typically an administrative protection against accidental disclosure within an organization.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] For example, before a hard drive is re-used within an organization, its contents may be cleared to prevent their accidental disclosure to the next user.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The storage media is made unusable for conventional equipment.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Effectiveness of destroying the media varies by medium and method.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Depending on recording density of the media, and/or the destruction technique, this may leave data recoverable by laboratory methods.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Conversely, destruction using appropriate techniques is the most secure method of preventing retrieval.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] A common method used to counter data remanence is to overwrite the storage media with new data.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] This is often called **wiping** or **shredding** a disk or file, by analogy to common methods of destroying print media, although the mechanism bears no similarity to these.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Because such a method can often be implemented in software alone, and may be able to selectively target only part of the media, it is a popular, low-cost option for some applications.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Overwriting is generally an acceptable method of clearing, as long as the media is writable and not damaged.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The simplest overwrite technique writes the same data everywhere—often just a pattern of all zeros.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] At a minimum, this will prevent the data from being retrieved simply by reading from the media again using standard system functions.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The UEFI in modern machines may offer an ATA class disk erase function as well.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The ATA-6 standard governs secure erases specifications.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Bitlocker is whole disk encryption and illegible without the key.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Writing a fresh GPT allows a new file system to be established.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Blocks will set empty but LBA read is illegible.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] New data will be unaffected and work fine.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] In an attempt to counter more advanced data recovery techniques, specific overwrite patterns and multiple passes have often been prescribed.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] These may be generic patterns intended to eradicate any trace signatures; an example is the seven-pass pattern *0xF6*, *0x00*, *0xFF*, *<random byte>*, *0x00*, *0xFF*, *<random byte>*, sometimes erroneously attributed to US standard DOD 5220.22-M.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] One challenge with overwriting is that some areas of the disk may be inaccessible, due to media degradation or other errors.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Software overwrite may also be problematic in high-security environments, which require stronger controls on data commingling than can be provided by the software in use.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The use of advanced storage technologies may also make file-based overwrite ineffective (see the related discussion below under ).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] There are specialized machines and software that are capable of doing overwriting.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The software can sometimes be a standalone operating system specifically designed for data destruction.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] There are also machines specifically designed to wipe hard drives to the department of defense specifications DOD 5220.22-M.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Writing zero to each block on hard disks and SSDs has the advantage of affording the firmware to deploy spare blocks when bad blocks are identified.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Bitlocker has the advantage that data is illegible without the key.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Seatools and other tools can erase disks with zero which is typical to revive old consumer class disks but they can wipe server disks albeit slowly.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Modern 28TB and larger disks have an enormous number of LBA48 blocks.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] 40TB and 60TB disks will take proportionately longer times to wipe.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Peter Gutmann investigated data recovery from nominally overwritten media in the mid-1990s.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] He suggested magnetic force microscopy may be able to recover such data, and developed specific patterns, for specific drive technologies, designed to counter such.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] These patterns have come to be known as the Gutmann method.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Gutmann's belief in the possibility of data recovery is based on many questionable assumptions and factual errors that indicate a low level of understanding of how hard drives work.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Daniel Feenberg, an economist at the private National Bureau of Economic Research, claims that the chances of overwritten data being recovered from a modern hard drive amount to "urban legend".
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] He also points to the "18+1⁄2-minute gap" Rose Mary Woods created on a tape of Richard Nixon discussing the Watergate break-in.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Erased information in the gap has not been recovered, and Feenberg claims doing so would be an easy task compared to recovery of a modern high density digital signal.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] As of November 2007, the United States Department of Defense considers overwriting acceptable for clearing magnetic media within the same security area/zone, but not as a sanitization method.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Only degaussing or physical destruction is acceptable for the latter.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] On the other hand, according to the 2014 NIST Special Publication 800-88 Rev.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Degaussing is the removal or reduction of a magnetic field of a disk or drive, using a device called a degausser that has been designed for the media being erased.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Applied to magnetic media, degaussing may purge an entire media element quickly and effectively.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Degaussing often renders hard disks inoperable, as it erases low-level formatting that is only done at the factory during manufacturing.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] In some cases, it is possible to return the drive to a functional state by having it serviced at the manufacturer.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] However, some modern degaussers use such a strong magnetic pulse that the motor that spins the platters may be destroyed in the degaussing process, and servicing may not be cost-effective.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Degaussed computer tape such as DLT can generally be reformatted and reused with standard consumer hardware.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] In some high-security environments, one may be required to use a degausser that has been approved for the task.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] For example, in US government and military jurisdictions, one may be required to use a degausser from the NSA's "Evaluated Products List".
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Encrypting data before it is stored on the media may mitigate concerns about data remanence.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] If the decryption key is strong and carefully controlled, it may effectively make any data on the media unrecoverable.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Even if the key is stored on the media, it may prove easier or quicker to overwrite just the key, versus the entire disk.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] This process is called crypto-shredding.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Encryption may be done on a file-by-file basis, or on the whole disk.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Cold boot attacks are one of the few possible methods for subverting a full-disk encryption method, as there is no possibility of storing the plain text key in an unencrypted section of the medium.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] See the section Complications: Data in RAM for further discussion.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Other side-channel attacks (such as keyloggers, acquisition of a written note containing the decryption key, or rubber-hose cryptanalysis) may offer a greater chance of success, but do not rely on weaknesses in the cryptographic method employed.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] As such, their relevance for this article is minor.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Thorough destruction of the underlying storage media is the most certain way to counter data remanence.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] However, the process is generally time-consuming, cumbersome, and may require extremely thorough methods, as even a small fragment of the media may contain large amounts of data.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Storage media may have areas which become inaccessible by normal means.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] For example, magnetic disks may develop new bad sectors after data has been written, and tapes require inter-record gaps.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Modern hard disks often feature reallocation of marginal sectors or tracks, automated in a way that the operating system would not need to work with it.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The problem is especially significant in solid-state drives (SSDs) that rely on relatively large relocated bad block tables.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Attempts to counter data remanence by overwriting may not be successful in such situations, as data remnants may persist in such nominally inaccessible areas.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Data storage systems with more sophisticated features may make overwrite ineffective, especially on a per-file basis.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] For example, journaling file systems increase the integrity of data by recording write operations in multiple locations, and applying transaction-like semantics; on such systems, data remnants may exist in locations "outside" the nominal file storage location.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Some file systems also implement copy-on-write or built-in revision control, with the intent that writing to a file never overwrites data in-place.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Furthermore, technologies such as RAID and anti-fragmentation techniques may result in file data being written to multiple locations, either by design (for fault tolerance), or as data remnants.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Wear leveling can also defeat data erasure, by relocating blocks between the time when they are originally written and the time when they are overwritten.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] As storage and system demands grow, the "junk data" files can be deleted as necessary to free up space; even if the deletion of "junk data" files is not secure, their initial nonsensitivity reduces to near zero the consequences of recovery of data remanent from them.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] As optical media are not magnetic, they are not erased by conventional degaussing.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Write-once optical media (CD-R, DVD-R, etc.) also cannot be purged by overwriting.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Rewritable optical media, such as CD-RW and DVD-RW, may be receptive to overwriting.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Methods for successfully sanitizing optical discs include delaminating or abrading the metallic data layer, shredding, incinerating, destructive electrical arcing (as by exposure to microwave energy), and submersion in a polycarbonate solvent (e.g., acetone).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Research from the Center for Magnetic Recording and Research, University of California, San Diego has uncovered problems inherent in erasing data stored on solid-state drives (SSDs).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Solid-state drives, which are flash-based, differ from hard-disk drives in two ways: first, in the way data is stored; and second, in the way the algorithms are used to manage and access that data.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] These differences can be exploited to recover previously erased data.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] SSDs maintain a layer of indirection between the logical addresses used by computer systems to access data and the internal addresses that identify physical storage.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] This layer of indirection hides idiosyncratic media interfaces and enhances SSD performance, reliability, and lifespan (see wear leveling), but it can also produce copies of the data that are invisible to the user and that a sophisticated attacker could recover.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] For sanitizing entire disks, sanitize commands built into the SSD hardware have been found to be effective when implemented correctly, and software-only techniques for sanitizing entire disks have been found to work most, but not all, of the time.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] In testing, none of the software techniques were effective for sanitizing individual files.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] These included well-known algorithms such as the Gutmann method, US DoD 5220.22-M, RCMP TSSIT OPS-II, Schneier 7 Pass, and Secure Empty Trash on macOS (a feature included in versions OS X 10.3-10.9).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The TRIM feature in many SSD devices, if properly implemented, will eventually erase data after it is deleted, but the process can take some time, typically several minutes.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Many older operating systems do not support this feature, and not all combinations of drives and operating systems work.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Data remanence has been observed in static random-access memory (SRAM), which is typically considered volatile (*i.e.*, the contents degrade with loss of external power).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] In one study, data retention was observed even at room temperature.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Data remanence has also been observed in dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Modern DRAM chips have a built-in self-refresh module, as they not only require a power supply to retain data, but must also be periodically refreshed to prevent their data contents from fading away from the capacitors in their integrated circuits.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Despite some memory degradation, authors of the above described study were able to take advantage of redundancy in the way keys are stored after they have been expanded for efficient use, such as in key scheduling.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] The authors recommend that computers be powered down, rather than be left in a "sleep" state, when not in physical control of the owner.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] In some cases, such as certain modes of the software program BitLocker, the authors recommend that a boot password or a key on a removable USB device be used.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] TRESOR is a kernel patch for Linux specifically intended to prevent cold boot attacks on RAM by ensuring that encryption keys are not accessible from user space and are stored in the CPU rather than system RAM whenever possible.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/data-remanence] Newer versions of the disk encryption software VeraCrypt can encrypt in-RAM keys and passwords on 64-bit Windows.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] Until the early 2000s, memory forensics was done on an ad hoc basis (termed *unstructured analysis*), often using generic data analysis tools like strings and grep.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] These tools are not specifically created for memory forensics, and therefore are difficult to use.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] In general, their primary usage is to extract text from the memory dump.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] Many operating systems provide features to kernel developers and end-users to actually create a snapshot of the physical memory for either debugging (e.g. core dump or Blue Screen of Death) purposes or experience enhancement (e.g. hibernation).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] In the case of Microsoft Windows, crash dumps and hibernation had been present since Microsoft Windows NT.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] Microsoft crash dumps had always been analyzable by Microsoft WinDbg, and Windows hibernation files (hiberfil.sys) are nowadays convertible in Microsoft crash dumps using utilities like MoonSols Windows Memory Toolkit designed by Matthieu Suiche.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] One significant step towards *structured analysis* was in a February 2004 article in SysAdmin Magazine, where Michael Ford demonstrated a more rigorous practice of memory forensics.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] In that article, he analyzes a memory based rootkit utilizing the existing Linux crash utility as well as two tools developed specifically to recover and analyze the memory forensically, memget and mempeek.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] In 2005, DFRWS issued a Memory Analysis Forensics Challenge.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] In response to this challenge, more tools in this generation, specifically designed to analyze memory dumps, were created - such as MoonSols, KntTools, the FATKit, VolaTools, and Volatility.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] These tools had knowledge of the operating system's internal data structures, and were thus capable of reconstructing the operating system's process list and process information.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] Although intended as research tools, they proved that operating system level memory forensics is possible and practical.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] Subsequently, several memory forensics tools were developed intended for practical use.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] These include both commercial tools like Responder PRO, Memoryze, winen, Belkasoft Live RAM Capturer, etc..
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] New features have been added, such as analysis of Linux and Mac OS X memory dumps, and substantial academic research has been carried out.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] Unlike Microsoft Windows, Mac OS X interest is relatively new and had only been initiated by Matthieu Suiche in 2010 during Black Hat Briefings security conference.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/memory-forensics] Currently, memory forensics is a standard component of incident response.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In modern technology, random-access memory takes the form of integrated circuit (IC) chips with MOS (metal–oxide–semiconductor) memory cells.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] RAM is normally associated with volatile types of memory where stored information is lost if power is removed.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The two main types of volatile random-access semiconductor memory are static random-access memory (SRAM) and dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Non-volatile RAM has also been developed and other types of non-volatile memories allow random access for read operations, but either do not allow write operations or have other kinds of limitations.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] These include most types of ROM and NOR flash memory.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The use of semiconductor RAM dates back to 1965 when IBM introduced the monolithic (single-chip) 16-bit SP95 SRAM chip for their System/360 Model 95 computer, and Toshiba used bipolar DRAM memory cells for its 180-bit Toscal BC-1411 electronic calculator, both based on bipolar transistors.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] While it offered higher speeds than magnetic-core memory, bipolar DRAM could not compete with the lower price of the then-dominant magnetic-core memory.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture in which there's a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The first commercial DRAM IC chip, the 1K Intel 1103, was introduced in October 1970.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Synchronous dynamic random-access memory (SDRAM) was reintroduced with the Samsung KM48SL2000 chip in 1992.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Early computers used relays, mechanical counters or delay lines for main memory functions.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Ultrasonic delay lines were serial devices which could only reproduce data in the order it was written.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Drum memory could be expanded at relatively low cost but efficient retrieval of memory items requires knowledge of the physical layout of the drum to optimize speed.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Latches built out of triode vacuum tubes, and later, out of discrete transistors, were used for smaller and faster memories such as registers.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Such registers were relatively large and too costly to use for large amounts of data; generally, only a few dozen or few hundred bits of such memory could be provided.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The first practical form of random-access memory was the Williams tube.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] It stored data as electrically charged spots on the face of a cathode-ray tube.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Since the electron beam of the CRT could read and write the spots on the tube in any order, memory was random access.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The capacity of the Williams tube was a few hundred to around a thousand bits, but it was much smaller, faster, and more power-efficient than using individual vacuum tube latches.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Developed at the University of Manchester in England, the Williams tube provided the medium on which the first electronically stored program was implemented in the Manchester Baby computer, which first successfully ran a program on 21 June, 1948.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In fact, rather than the Williams tube memory being designed for the Baby, the Baby was a testbed to demonstrate the reliability of the memory.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Magnetic-core memory was invented in 1947 and developed up until the mid-1970s.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] It became a widespread form of random-access memory, relying on an array of magnetized rings.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] By changing the sense of each ring's magnetization, data could be stored with one bit stored per ring.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Since every ring had a combination of address wires to select and read or write it, access to any memory location in any sequence was possible.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Magnetic core memory was the standard form of computer memory until displaced by semiconductor memory in integrated circuits (ICs) during the early 1970s.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Prior to the development of integrated read-only memory (ROM) circuits, *permanent* (or *read-only*) random-access memory was often constructed using diode matrices driven by address decoders, or specially wound core rope memory planes.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Semiconductor memory appeared in the 1960s with bipolar memory, which used bipolar transistors.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Although it was faster, it could not compete with the lower price of magnetic core memory.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In 1957, Frosch and Derick manufactured the first silicon dioxide field-effect transistors at Bell Labs, the first transistors in which drain and source were adjacent at the surface.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Subsequently, in 1960, a team demonstrated a working MOSFET at Bell Labs.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] This led to the development of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) memory by John Schmidt at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1964.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In addition to higher speeds, MOS semiconductor memory was cheaper and consumed less power than magnetic core memory.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The development of silicon-gate MOS integrated circuit (MOS IC) technology by Federico Faggin at Fairchild in 1968 enabled the production of MOS memory chips.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] MOS memory overtook magnetic core memory as the dominant memory technology in the early 1970s.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Integrated bipolar static random-access memory (SRAM) was invented by Robert H.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Norman at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1963.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] It was followed by the development of MOS SRAM by John Schmidt at Fairchild in 1964.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] SRAM became an alternative to magnetic-core memory, but required six MOS transistors for each bit of data.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Commercial use of SRAM began in 1965, when IBM introduced the SP95 memory chip for the System/360 Model 95.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) allowed replacement of a 4- or 6-transistor latch circuit by a single transistor for each memory bit, greatly increasing memory density at the cost of volatility.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Data was stored in the tiny capacitance of each transistor and had to be periodically refreshed every few milliseconds before the charge could leak away.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Toshiba's Toscal BC-1411 electronic calculator, which was introduced in 1965, used a form of capacitor bipolar DRAM, storing 180-bit data on discrete memory cells, consisting of germanium bipolar transistors and capacitors.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Capacitors had also been used for earlier memory schemes, such as the drum of the Atanasoff–Berry Computer, the Williams tube and the Selectron tube.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In 1966, Robert Dennard, while examining the characteristics of MOS technology, found it was capable of building capacitors, and that storing a charge or no charge on the MOS capacitor could represent the 1 and 0 of a bit, and the MOS transistor could control writing the charge to the capacitor.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] This led to his development of modern DRAM architecture for which there is a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In 1967, Dennard filed a patent under IBM for a single-transistor DRAM memory cell, based on MOS technology.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The first commercial DRAM IC chip was the Intel 1103, which was manufactured on an 8 μm MOS process with a capacity of 1 kbit, and was released in 1970.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The earliest DRAMs were often synchronized with the CPU clock and were used with early microprocessors.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In the mid-1970s, DRAMs moved to the asynchronous design, but in the 1990s returned to synchronous operation.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In 1992 Samsung released KM48SL2000, which had a capacity of 16 Mbit.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The first commercial double data rate SDRAM was Samsung's 64 Mbit DDR SDRAM, released in June 1998.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] GDDR (graphics DDR) is a form of SGRAM (synchronous graphics RAM), which was first released by Samsung as a 16 Mbit memory chip in 1998.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In general, the term *RAM* refers solely to solid-state memory devices, and more specifically the main memory in most computers.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The two widely used forms of modern RAM are static RAM (SRAM) and dynamic RAM (DRAM).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In SRAM, a bit of data is stored using the state of a memory cell, typically using six MOSFETs.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] This form of RAM is more expensive to produce, but is generally faster and requires less static power than DRAM.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In modern computers, SRAM is often used as cache memory for the CPU.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] DRAM stores a bit of data using a transistor and capacitor pair (typically a MOSFET and MOS capacitor, respectively), which together comprise a DRAM cell.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The capacitor holds a high or low charge (1 or 0, respectively), and the transistor acts as a switch that lets the control circuitry on the chip read the capacitor's state of charge or change it.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] As this form of memory is less expensive to produce than static RAM, it is the predominant form of computer memory used in modern computers.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Both static and dynamic RAM are considered *volatile*, as their state is lost when power is removed from the system.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] By contrast, read-only memory (ROM) stores data by permanently enabling or disabling selected transistors, such that the memory cannot be altered.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Writable variants of ROM (such as EEPROM and NOR flash) share properties of both ROM and RAM, enabling data to persist without power and to be updated without requiring special equipment.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] ECC memory (which can be either SRAM or DRAM) includes special circuitry to detect and/or correct random faults (memory errors) in the stored data, using parity bits or error correction codes.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The memory cell is the fundamental building block of computer memory.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The memory cell is an electronic circuit that stores one bit of binary information.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The cell can be set to store a logic 1 (high voltage level) and reset to store a logic 0 (low voltage level).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Its value is maintained until it is changed by the set/reset process.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The value in the memory cell can be accessed by reading it.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In SRAM, the memory cell is a type of flip-flop circuit, usually implemented using FETs.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] This means that SRAM requires very low power when not being accessed, but it is complex, expensive and has low storage density.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] A second type, DRAM, is based around a capacitor.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Charging and discharging this capacitor can store a 1 or a 0 in the cell.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] However, the charge in this capacitor slowly leaks away and must be refreshed periodically.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Because of this refresh process, DRAM uses more power, but it can achieve greater storage densities and lower unit costs compared to SRAM.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] To be useful, memory cells must be readable and writable.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Within the RAM device, multiplexing and demultiplexing circuitry is used to select memory cells.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Typically, a RAM device has a set of address lines $A_{0},A_{1},...A_{n}$ , and for each combination of bits that may be applied to these lines, a set of memory cells are selected.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Due to this addressing, RAM devices virtually always have a memory capacity that is a power of two.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Usually, several memory cells share the same address.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] For example, a 4-bit-wide RAM chip has four memory cells for each address.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Often the width of the memory and that of the microprocessor are different; for a 32-bit microprocessor, eight 4-bit RAM chips would be needed.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Often, more addresses are needed than can be provided by a single device.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In that case, multiple devices are used, with external multiplexors used to select the device assigned to a specific address range.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] RAM is often byte addressable, although word-addressable RAM also exists.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Many computer systems have a memory hierarchy consisting of processor registers, on-die SRAM caches, external caches, DRAM, memory paging systems and virtual memory or swap space on a SSD or hard drive.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] This entire pool of memory may be referred to as RAM from a programming perspective.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The overall goal of using a memory hierarchy is to obtain the fastest possible average access time while minimizing the total cost of the entire memory system.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In addition to serving as temporary storage and working space for the operating system and applications, RAM is used in numerous other ways.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Most modern operating systems employ a method, known as virtual memory, of extending RAM capacity.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] A portion of the computer's hard drive or SSD is set aside for a *paging file* or a *scratch partition*, and the combination of physical RAM and the paging file forms the system's total memory.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] For example, if a computer has 2 GB of RAM and a 1 GB page file, the operating system has 3 GB total memory available to it.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] When the system runs low on physical memory, it can swap portions of RAM to the paging file to make room for new data.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] When the previously swapped information is needed again, another swap is performed to read the information back into RAM.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Excessive use of this mechanism results in thrashing and generally hampers overall system performance, mainly because hard drives are far slower than RAM.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Software can *partition* a portion of a computer's RAM, allowing it to act as a much faster hard drive that is called a RAM drive.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] A RAM drive typically loses the stored data when the computer is shut down.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Sometimes, the contents of a relatively slow ROM chip are copied to RAM to allow for shorter access times.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The ROM chip is then disabled while the initialized memory locations are switched in on the same block of addresses (often write-protected).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] This process, sometimes called *shadowing*, is fairly common in both computers and embedded systems.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] As a common example, the BIOS in typical personal computers often has an option called "use shadow BIOS" or similar.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] When enabled, functions that rely on data from the BIOS's ROM instead use DRAM locations (most can also toggle shadowing of video card ROM or other ROM sections).
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Free memory is reduced by the size of the shadowed ROMs.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Depending on the system, this may not result in increased performance and may cause incompatibilities.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] For example, some hardware may be inaccessible to the operating system if shadow RAM is used.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] On some systems, the benefit may be hypothetical because the BIOS is not used after booting.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Some virtual private network services utilize RAM servers to keep all runtime state, including session metadata and cryptographic material, in volatile memory.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] This is intended to improve security relative to disk-backed designs.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] In such a design, no data is written to hard drives; all information resides in volatile memory and is erased whenever the server is powered off or rebooted.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The **memory wall** is the growing disparity of speed between CPU and the response time of memory (known as memory latency) outside the CPU chip.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] An important reason for this disparity is the limited communication bandwidth beyond chip boundaries.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] From 1986 to 2000, CPU speed improved at an annual rate of 55% while off-chip memory response time only improved at 10%.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Given these trends, it was expected that memory latency would become an overwhelming bottleneck in computer performance.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Another reason for the disparity is the enormous increase in the size of memory since the start of the PC revolution in the 1980s.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Originally, PCs contained less than 1 megabyte of RAM, which often had a response time of 1 CPU clock cycle, meaning that it required 0 wait states.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Larger memory units are inherently slower than smaller ones of the same type, simply because it takes longer for signals to traverse a larger circuit.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Constructing a memory unit of many gigabytes with a response time of one clock cycle is difficult or impossible.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Modern CPUs often still have 0 wait state cache memory, but, due to the bandwidth limitations of chip-to-chip communication, it must reside on the same chip as the CPU cores.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] It must also be constructed from static RAM, which is far more expensive than the dynamic RAM used for larger memories.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] CPU speed improvements slowed significantly, partly due to major physical barriers and partly because CPU designs have already hit the memory wall in some sense.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Intel summarized these causes in a 2005 document.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The RC delays in signal transmission were also noted in "Clock Rate versus IPC: The End of the Road for Conventional Microarchitectures" which projected a maximum of 12.5% average annual CPU performance improvement between 2000 and 2014.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] A different concept is the processor-memory performance gap, which can be addressed by 3D integrated circuits that reduce the distance between the control logic and memory cells that are further apart in a 2D chip.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Memory subsystem design requires a focus on the gap, which is widening over time.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] The main method of bridging the gap is the use of caches; small amounts of high-speed memory that houses data associated with recent operations near the processor, speeding up access to this data in cases where they are called upon frequently.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Multiple levels of caching have been developed to deal with the widening gap, and the performance of high-speed modern computers relies on evolving caching techniques.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] There can be up to a 53% difference between the growth in speed of processor and the lagging speed of main memory access.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/random-access-memory] Fast, cheap, non-volatile solid state drives have replaced some functions formerly performed by RAM, such as holding certain data for immediate availability in server farms – 1 terabyte of SSD storage can be had for $200, while 1 TB of RAM would cost thousands of dollars.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] Volatile memory has several uses, including as primary storage.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] In addition to usually being faster than forms of mass storage such as a hard disk drive, volatility can protect sensitive information, as it becomes unavailable on power-down.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] Most general-purpose random-access memory (RAM) is volatile.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] There are two kinds of volatile RAM: dynamic and static.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] Even though both types need continuous electrical current to retain data, there are some important differences between them.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] Dynamic RAM (DRAM) is very popular due to its cost-effectiveness.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] DRAM stores each bit of information in a different capacitor within the integrated circuit.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] DRAM chips need just one single capacitor and one transistor to store each bit of information.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] This makes it space-efficient and inexpensive.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] The main advantage of static RAM (SRAM) is that it is much faster than dynamic RAM.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] SRAM does not need continuous electrical refreshes, but it still requires constant current to sustain the difference in voltage.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] Every single bit in a static RAM chip needs a cell of six transistors, whereas dynamic RAM requires only one capacitor and one transistor.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] As a result, SRAM is unable to accomplish the storage capabilities of the DRAM family.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatile-memory] SRAM is commonly used as CPU cache and for processor registers and in networking devices.
[src:memory-forensics-volatility/volatility-memory-forensics] Volatility was created by Aaron Walters, drawing on academic research he did in memory forensics.
